    # [Scene: Etta's Greenhouse (The Nursery) | Night]
    hide mateo_alvarez
    hide ari_tanaka

    scene bg ch15_f7128a_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rain fingers at the panes; the heater hums steady]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A lower-register violin drone with clipped, urgent percussion]
    "Etta moves among seedlings like prayer. Her hands are quick and deliberate, stained with peat. She looks up as you enter, and for a second the lines on her face rewrite themselves into relief."
    show etta_hargrove at left:
        zoom 0.7

    etta_hargrove "You look like winter ate your mouth, child. Sit."
    show ari_tanaka at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ari_tanaka "They've filed another delay. And a counterclaim. Mara says the narrative's flipping. Mateo's—"

    etta_hargrove "Mateo's tired. So are you. But this—' (she taps a tray of salicornia) '—this is still here. Roots don't make lawyers' speeches, but they do keep the soil. You'll need both: the words and the soil."

    ari_tanaka "We need people to keep showing up. We need the audit to land before the firm frames 'pause' as 'obstruction.'"

    etta_hargrove "You did the right thing. Saying 'not now' is harder when the sea is knocking. But some deals aren't worth the land they sign away.' (she spreads her hands, palms up) 'Remember why you started."

    ari_tanaka "I started because I wanted the town to keep its edges. I didn't expect to spend nights counting clauses."

    etta_hargrove "Clauses are useless if the greenhouse burns. Now—' (she stands, voice steel) '—you must go to the plaza. Rally the volunteers for the storm watches. We keep lines of human eyes. We keep the boats ready. We fight a different front."
    "Ari Tanaka: (there's a tightness in your chest like a dropped stone) 'I'm afraid, Etta.'"

    etta_hargrove "Good. Fear keeps you honest. But don't let it paralyze you. Lead with it."

    menu:
        "Volunteer to lead night storm watches at the harbor":
            "You pull your jacket tight and feel a cold kind of readiness—this is concrete work. The memory of earlier storms sharpens your fingers."
        "Stay at the greenhouse to help Etta secure plants and supplies":
            "You kneel in the soil, hands going numb with peat. The physicality steadies you; it's prayer in a different currency."

