    # [Scene: Montage — Campaign & Legal Spiral | Over weeks]
    hide etta_hargrove
    hide ari_tanaka

    scene bg ch15_f7128a_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A cacophony of courthouse footsteps, newsroom clacks, and weather reports overlapping]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A crescendoing, relentless pulse; woodwinds slicing anxiety]
    "Mara's articles land like stones. Some land cleanly—local outlets pick up the audit's requested points; some are rebutted by paid op-eds with glossy images of engineered seawalls. The community responds unevenly: neighbors double down, others lose"
    "hope and sell on terms they previously rejected. Fundraisers thin. Grants stall in bureaucratic limbo. The audit's progress is glacial inside legal mazes."
    "You stand in municipal halls, hands raw from signing petitions and affidavits. You read clause after clause until the letters blur. The town organizes a legal defense fund. Volunteers live on sandwiches and coffee and the idea that process will be justice."
    # [Scene: Workshop | One Week Before the Storm]

    scene bg ch15_f7128a_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Dissonant chords; a single violin shrieks]
    "Mateo Alvarez is quieter, sharper. The strain shows in small betrayals: his jokes curtailed, his eyes darting to a plane ticket on the bench."
    show mateo_alvarez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mateo_alvarez "They offered me a project in the south—modular protections in a different town. Fast funding. Fewer lawyers. They'd let me build."
    show ari_tanaka at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ari_tanaka "You could still split your time."
    "Mateo Alvarez: (shakes his head) 'Not with you here. Not when the pilot needs constant oversight. This is bigger than me wanting to leave—it's that I can't watch this timeline and pretend it won't cost people"
    "houses. I thought staying and fighting would be the right thing. But the fight is grinding the work to bits.'"

    ari_tanaka "So you'll go."

    mateo_alvarez "I have to build in a place that will let me build now. Maybe I can come back with a proof that helps Tidebridge. Maybe I'm cowardly. Maybe I'm pragmatic.' (he looks at you, eyes rimmed) 'I don't know which yet."
    "Ari Tanaka: (you feel the room tilt) 'If you go—promise me you'll make sure the pilot design is open-source. That the blueprints are public. That no one can lock this behind corporate keys.'"
    "Mateo Alvarez: (after a beat) 'I promise. But I can't stay and watch our timelines fall apart while the sea gets louder.'"
    "The line between personal and political snaps. Mateo leaves the next morning with a backpack and a stack of hard drives. He presses a thin bracelet into your palm—woven, sun-faded. He doesn't say 'goodbye', only, 'Call me when it's safe.'"
    # [Scene: Storm Night | Very Late — The Climax]
    hide mateo_alvarez
    hide ari_tanaka

    scene bg ch15_f7128a_8 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Violent wind, metal snapping, distant alarms; the town's usual sounds replaced by elemental percussion]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Orchestral chaos—strings rasping, drums like battering, brass crashing]
    "You are on the harbor with a handful of volunteers—spotlights, flashlights swinging like shipwrecked stars. The injunctions and audits are still active but irrelevant to the physics that now shove at foundations. The sea doesn't care for petitions. It answers with preference: what is already emptied it will take faster."
    "You are watching the levee when you hear the first tearing—a plank, then a moan like a giant waking. A cluster of houses near the old eastward pier, long-marked as 'vulnerable', takes a surge. You muscle forward—radio crackles make everything a thin line."

    "Volunteer" "There's someone on the upper deck!"
    show ari_tanaka at left:
        zoom 0.7

    ari_tanaka "Get the ladder! Keep that line tight!"
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A board breaks with a sound like a brittle thing being snapped. The harbor light topples. People shout; the storm answers with a sound like the sky grinding teeth.]
    "You throw your weight against the ladder. Salt stings your eyes. For a moment—long as a held breath—you see a roofline vanish beneath water. A child's lamp swings. A voice that was talking into a radio disappears into the slap of waves."
    "Inside your chest, a great animal wakes: a private avalanche of all the times you thought time would be on your side. You swivel your head. Etta's greenhouse is a rectangle of warm light across the"
    "water; then a gust strips its outline away. You hear later that the seawall—an older, ad-hoc mound of sandbags and driftwood—gave way just past midnight."
    "The volunteers fight like hands clinging to a promise. People are pulled from porches, soaked and shaking. A small boat, one meant for light tide runs, groans and then becomes a coffin of possibility as it flips."
    "You manage to pull someone across the wet dock—an older woman, shaking. Her hands smell like peat and salt; her teeth chatter through a litany of names. She holds your wrist like a supplicant."

    "Older Woman" "My—our—place is—"

    ari_tanaka "You're safe. You're safe now. We'll find—"
    "Her eyes flick to your camera, to the tote of petitions sloshing at your feet, and for a second you see accusation and gratitude braid together."
    "Ari Tanaka (internal): The audit. The injunctions. The hearings. Paper has weight when it is in time, but tonight the sea is the only thing measuring value."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A boom; a pier collapses in a gout of water. The highest arousal point—the storm's teeth—strikes and will not let go.]
    "You run. You run until your lungs burn and your legs are numb. You pull bodies out of water, pass them forward into human chains, and in each movement there is the terrible calculus of what"
    "you could have done earlier, what you delayed, and whether the act of demanding accountability counts when someone is drowning."
    # [Scene: Aftermath — Dawn]
    hide ari_tanaka

    scene bg ch15_f7128a_9 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low sobbing layered under the distant whine of generators; gulls screaming]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse piano, slow, with a hollow undertow]
    "The audit eventually finds its way into public view; Mara's reporting is incisive and relentless. The transcripts show that the firm had clauses written to allow aggressive action under loosely defined emergencies. They had plans that"
    "could have privileged private servitude of the shoreline. Your decision to demand audits uncovered those words in legal light. On paper—names, clauses, the firm's culpability—are exposed. Councilor Rosa uses the findings to craft new, binding covenants"
    "that protect public access and forbid buyouts. In the sterile language of policy, your principles win."
    "On the ground, the win is brittle."
    "Rows of houses are gone or condemned. A shoreline community you worked beside for years is dispersed across trailers and borrowed couches. Some neighbors took buyouts earlier than they otherwise would have, others lost everything when"
    "the storm outpaced the injunctions. The legal record will stand for the town's future; the immediate reality is loss."
    "Etta's greenhouse survived in part—its back wall bowed inward; many trays were ruined, but some seedlings cling stubbornly. She sits amid overturned pots, hands deep in mud."
    show etta_hargrove at left:
        zoom 0.7

    etta_hargrove "We kept some. Not enough for everyone. But some."
    "You kneel beside her, dirt caking your palms, and for a long, careful moment the two of you are only human and mud."
    show ari_tanaka at right:
        zoom 0.7

    ari_tanaka "They tried to protect us with speed and force. We tried to protect ourselves with time and transparency. Both had teeth."

    etta_hargrove "Yes. Teeth. You got the teeth on paper, Ari. But teeth in mouths are another thing."
    "Mateo Alvarez returns bright-eyed with a suitcase and a stack of printed designs—open-source files waiting in your inbox. He kisses your forehead the first time without the hesitation he's recorded in other days."
    show mateo_alvarez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    mateo_alvarez "I—sent everything I could while I was away. I built with other towns. They gave me space to work. I hope—"

    ari_tanaka "Did it help?"

    mateo_alvarez "Maybe. Some models we tested are already in place where my team is. But Tidebridge—' (he exhales) '—you bought time with a paper shield. Time is messy."
    "Ari Tanaka (internal): He left, and he returned with tools and receipts; but a person cannot be a bridge unless they stand in the same tide. The bargain felt like a ledger: gains on paper, losses in skin."
    "Mara hands you a sheaf of printouts—her reporting did what journalism can: it named, it showed, it made people angry in all the right and wrong ways."
    hide etta_hargrove
    show mara_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    mara_chen "You gave the town a narrative that isn't only 'delay equals danger.' You made it complex. People will remember that. But—' (her voice drops) '—they will also remember the houses."
    "You look around. A neighbor you cannot name sits on the curb, wrapped in a thermal blanket, a small cardboard box of salvaged items at her feet. She looks at you with an expression that has"
    "both softness and accusation. You have learned, in the most brutal way, that moral clarity on paper doesn't erase cold or hunger."
    # [Scene: The Pier | Dusk, Weeks Later]
    hide ari_tanaka
    hide mateo_alvarez
    hide mara_chen

    scene bg ch15_f7128a_10 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Minimal cello; a single, steady drone]
    "You walk alone along the water's edge, your camera empty in the tote that once held proof and promise. The audit's signatures glimmer faintly, a legal victory posted in the municipal ledger. Council meets; covenants pass."
    "The firm is fined and forced to revise contracts for other towns. Elio's team retreats to a new posture, chastened by public exposure. On paper, there is accountability."
    "But your hands still smell of peat and salt. The town is smaller in places. The faces you recognize are fewer, the docks half-reclaimed by the sea. Mateo's bracelet is on your wrist; you run your thumb over the thread and it feels like a memory."
    "You think of Etta's steady, wrinkled fingers; of Mara's exhausted, unblinking gaze; of the volunteers who gave so much. You think of the moment the board went down in the storm and of the longer, colder"
    "decision that came after—when some families chose shelter elsewhere because staying was a daily negotiation no one could sustain."
    "Ari Tanaka (internal): We stopped a corporate overreach. We won a principle. We paid a price that will sit in the town's bones for years."
    "You lift your camera and take a photo of the horizon. The shot is washed-out, a study in grays; in the file, you file the moment under 'After.' The camera shutter clicks like a knell."

    scene bg ch15_f7128a_11 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: One aching piano chord that resolves into silence]
    "You take one last, steadying breath and fold your hands around the camera strap."

    scene bg ch15_f7128a_12 at full_bg
